## Module Structure

```
gtcx-zkp/src/
  lib.rs                          -- crate root, re-exports
  zk.rs                           -- ZkCircuit trait, Groth16Bn254 backend, ZkError, batch verification
  zk/
    ceremony.rs                   -- Trusted setup ceremony (single-party, MPC, automation)
    circuits/
      mod.rs                      -- Circuit module re-exports
      gci.rs                      -- GciThresholdCircuit
      location.rs                 -- LocationRegionCircuit (bounding box, convex polygon)
      ownership.rs                -- AssetOwnershipCircuit (Pedersen commitment)
      range.rs                    -- AmountRangeCircuit (u64 range proof)
    audit.rs                      -- Circuit constraint auditing, R1CS analysis
    soundness.rs                  -- Adversarial soundness testing suite
    compose.rs                    -- Cross-circuit composition, ComposedStatement builder
    metadata.rs                   -- ProofMetadata, provenance, prover identity commitment
    store.rs                      -- Content-addressable proof storage, expiration, indexing
    metrics.rs                    -- ZK metrics, Prometheus export
  bbs.rs                          -- BBS+ selective disclosure for verifiable credentials
  fixed_point.rs                  -- Fixed-point arithmetic for location circuit
```


## Technical Notes

- **Primary library**: `arkworks` suite (`ark-groth16`, `ark-bn254`, `ark-relations`, `ark-serialize`, `ark-std`)
- **Curve**: BN254 (alt_bn128) for Groth16 proofs; provides approximately 110 bits of security, sufficient for medium-term deployments. The `ZkCircuit` trait is designed to support curve migration if BN254 security is deemed insufficient in the future.
- **BLS12-381**: May be evaluated as an alternative curve for applications requiring higher security margin (~128 bits) or pairing-friendly properties needed by BBS+.
- **BBS+ library**: Evaluate `bbs` or `zkryptium` crate for selective disclosure; must support unlinkable selective disclosure and be compatible with the W3C BBS Signature Scheme draft. Selection decision to be documented in `kora-crypto/src/bbs.rs` module comments.
- **Fixed-point arithmetic**: Location circuit uses fixed-point representation with 6 decimal places scaled by 10^6 to convert GPS coordinates to integers. This avoids floating-point non-determinism in R1CS constraint systems. The fixed-point module is implemented separately in `fixed_point.rs` for reuse.
- **Security -- Zeroizing**: All private witness data, toxic waste, and secret key material is wrapped in `Zeroizing<T>` from the `zeroize` crate. This guarantees that sensitive data is zeroed on drop, even in panic scenarios. No private inputs appear in log output, debug format implementations, or serialized forms.
- **Fuzz testing**: All proof and key deserialization paths (`from_bytes()`) require `cargo-fuzz` targets per the project Cryptographic Definition of Done. Minimum 10 million iterations before merge for each fuzz target.


## Risks

| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|------|------------|--------|------------|
| arkworks API instability between minor versions | Medium | Medium | Pin exact crate versions in `Cargo.toml`; maintain thin abstraction layer via `ZkCircuit` trait (ZKP-US-001) to isolate downstream code from arkworks API changes |
| Groth16 trusted setup is a single point of trust; compromised ceremony enables proof forgery | Medium | High | Support MPC ceremony with multiple independent participants (ZKP-US-002, ZKP-US-015); document threat model; require at least 3 participants for production ceremonies |
| Proof generation may exceed 5s target for complex circuits, especially location polygon containment | Medium | Medium | Profile constraint count early in Sprint 19; simplify region representation to bounding-box only if polygon constraint count is prohibitive; optimize with parallel witness generation |
| BBS+ crate ecosystem is less mature than arkworks; potential API instability or missing features | High | Medium | Evaluate multiple crates (`bbs`, `zkryptium`) before committing; maintain fallback to attribute-level Groth16 proofs if BBS+ crate is unsuitable; limit BBS+ story to 1 point to contain risk |
| BN254 security level (~110 bits) may be insufficient for long-term deployments as computational power increases | Low | High | Design `ZkCircuit` trait to support curve migration (associated types, not hardcoded BN254); monitor NIST and IACR cryptographic recommendations; BLS12-381 migration path documented |


## Definition of Done -- Epic Level

This epic is complete when:

1. All 17 user stories are implemented and pass their acceptance criteria
2. All unit tests pass with > 90% code coverage across the ZK module
3. All `criterion` benchmarks meet their performance targets (proof gen <5s p95, verify <100ms p95, batch 100 <5s)
4. All `cargo-fuzz` targets have completed 10 million+ iterations without crashes
5. All four application circuits pass the soundness testing suite (ZKP-US-012) with zero false proofs accepted
6. Constraint audits (ZKP-US-011) are documented for all four circuits
7. A full end-to-end integration test exists that: generates setup keys, creates a proof for each circuit type, serializes and deserializes the proofs, verifies them individually and in a batch, and composes a multi-circuit statement
8. BBS+ selective disclosure produces valid proofs that are information-theoretically hiding and unlinkable
9. All cryptographic code satisfies the Cryptographic Definition of Done from the master roadmap: audited libraries, zeroizing keys, no unsafe code, constant-time comparisons where applicable, fuzz testing, security review
10. Setup ceremony automation can execute a reproducible 3-party MPC ceremony with auditable transcript
11. Proof storage, indexing, and metrics are operational with Prometheus export
12. Documentation: module-level doc comments, threat model assumptions, binary format specifications, constraint counts, and performance measurements
13. Security review completed and approved for all PRs


